                <h3>Whirlpool</h3>
                <p>Whirlpool refrigerators are known for their reliability and wide range of models, from basic to high-end. Repair costs for Whirlpool refrigerators can vary significantly depending on the specific model and the issue at hand. On average, homeowners might expect to pay between <b>$150 to $400</b> for common repairs such as replacing a thermostat, door gasket, or water filter. More complex repairs, like compressor replacement, can be pricier, potentially ranging from <b>$500 to $800</b>. Whirlpool's extensive network of authorized repair technicians can sometimes help reduce costs by ensuring that replacements and repairs use genuine parts, thereby extending the lifespan of the appliance.</p>

                <h3>Samsung</h3>
                <p>Samsung refrigerators are renowned for their advanced technology and sleek designs, often featuring digital displays, smart capabilities, and multiple cooling zones. The cost to repair a Samsung refrigerator can be on the higher side due to these sophisticated features. Typical repair costs can range from <b>$200 to $500</b> for issues such as malfunctioning sensors, water dispensers, or ice makers. More serious problems, like a faulty compressor, might cost upwards of <b>$600 to $900</b>. Given the complexity of Samsung's electronics, it's crucial to use certified repair services to maintain the integrity of the appliance and ensure accurate diagnostics.</p>

                <h3>LG</h3>
                <p>LG refrigerators are celebrated for their innovative designs and energy efficiency. Repair costs for LG models can vary but generally fall within a similar range to other high-tech brands. Expect to pay between <b>$200 and $450</b> for common repairs like fixing a defective evaporator fan or replacing a damaged door gasket. If the problem involves the compressor or other critical cooling system components, the cost can escalate to between <b>$600 and $1,000</b>. LG's use of proprietary technology often necessitates specialized knowledge and parts, so it's advisable to seek out authorized repair services to ensure quality repairs and preserve warranty conditions.</p>

                <h3>GE</h3>
                <p>GE refrigerators are a staple in many homes, offering a balance of affordability and functionality. Repair costs for GE models are typically moderate, with common fixes such as replacing thermostats, door seals, or water filters often costing between <b>$150 and $350</b>. For more intricate repairs, like those involving the compressor or electronic control boards, costs can rise to between <b>$400 and $700</b>. The availability of parts and the widespread presence of GE-certified technicians can help keep repair costs reasonable and turnaround times quick, making GE a practical choice for many households.</p>

